  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "05f7aba51661ac49",
      "text": "If you have circles drawn on a piece of paper, it is quite natural to [[give]] them [[Name]]s to be able to distinguish between them."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8d0b0c693e429cd1",
      "text": "An important fact to notice is that, once you [[remove]] the names, the circles are quite equivalent to each other. Thus, it is clear that the most disparately named distinctions can be on an equal footing when it comes to the meaning of carving a portion out of the universe of possible things. It is perfectly normal for distinctions to be quite mundane, lacking a special place on the piece of paper."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "941cdd4f0375f1d3",
      "text": "For example, if you were to look around, you would see things. However, what you perceive as things are [[Region]]s of your perception space defined by a [[Boundary]]. The boundary is set by you, the observer, according to your intentions."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cb19ade29a24026f",
      "text": "If you pay enough attention to let some regions be determined by means of boundaries, but do not give names to these regions, you will see that they are quite similar to each other as far as bounded regions go. At this point, they are distinctions without a name, and as such they are quite equivalent to each other."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "256a039b0cfda67b",
      "text": "Names are labels which are applied on distinctions, just as if they were post-it notes. This leads to the following principle, which is extremely important to keep in mind at all times: *labels should never be confused with the labelled objects*."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3a39a8167093f6af",
      "text": "A language can be constructed by means of a set of labels which, considered as distinctions named as themselves, have a particular relationship between each other. The relationships between the labels can be thought of as the connections between the nodes of a graph in which the labels are the nodes."
    },
